node.text:
Though smack dab in the middle of Los Angeles’ vibrant East Side, this home feels like a secret hideaway. Steps from a street lined with apartment buildings, modest older homes, and commercial warehouses, the single-level house, with just one window on the front facade, looks inward, becoming more open as you move through it to the surprisingly lush backyard. “We wanted to explore indoor/outdoor living in a different way,” says owner Mark Motonaga of @rioshome, who renovated the 1920s-era home with his partner, artist Guy Clouse. Read the complete feature on Atwater Hideaway, nominated in this year’s Dwell Design Awards, when you visit dwell.com/design-awards
–

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Dwell on July 29, 2021. May be an image of furniture and indoor.

node.text:
Ezequiel Adelmo Manasseri and María Sol Depetris had been searching for three years when they finally found their future apartment. Occupying the full second floor and an attic in one of Rosario, Argentina’s many "French-style" buildings—Haussmann-esque constructions dating from the early 20th century—the space had most recently housed an accounting firm. The walls were painted a shabby pastel yellow, but it still had many original plaster details and a "casa chorizo" layout, a succession of rooms that open to an exterior gallery. The young couple, cofounders of both the architecture studio @manasseridepetris and furniture brand Citrino (@citrino.citrino), knew they had come across something special. That was 2015. After four years of living there, it was time to make the 1,600-square-foot space a little more practical by creating private space. So they embarked on a renovation, turning the attic into an en suite bedroom, and covering the walls with a whited-out palette with bursts of color courtesy of the furniture they designed. The primary objective was to preserve the spirit of the property, so they brought in artisans, many of whom are retired, to exercise near-forgotten skills of restoring ornamental plaster features. The most striking change, pictured in the first slide, is a new stair enclosure protruding out into the apartment’s gallery that leads from a library up to the studio-turned-bedroom. It was fabricated from malleable metal-alloy panels, molded, erected, and spray painted in situ. Eze laughs, explaining that they used a car spray paint color called Gran Prix, the closest they could get to International Klein Blue while avoiding the headache of creating the formula themselves. Derek White jokes that he was in his second year of university when he "started vetting architects” for his future home. “That’s when I met Liani—I don’t know if we would have been friends if we didn’t share a sense of aesthetics," Derek says wryly as Liani Douglas listens in. But friends they became, and some 14 years later, when Derek and his partner, Jean Banks, came across a dilapidated, 80-year-old cottage in Cape Town’s Newlands Village, he immediately called Douglas & Company (@do_andco), the architectural firm Douglas had founded with her husband, Jan. The 860-square-foot cottage Derek had found was in rough shape, but part of the fun was determining how to make the most of an idyllic lot. “Initially, it wasn’t clear to us what the solution was," he says. "But we knew we wanted outdoor space around the house, especially for our two dogs." Douglas came back with plans for a holistic renovation: She would demolish the existing outbuildings to make room for adjacent gardens and gut the interiors of the cottage, preserving only the original foundation as a starting point for the new residence. By adding a steel frame, she could expand upward to create a second level and a loft. "It was so obvious that this was the only way this should work," Derek remembers. "It felt 100 percent right." O‘ahu’s North Shore is known for its epic surf, but it wasn’t the big waves that drew Sara and James Davis. It was a mountain—specifically Mount Ka‘ala, the island’s highest peak. The couple and their three children, who live an hour away in Honolulu, dreamed of a getaway in the area’s quiet interior. "We’re nature people," James explains. "We love to be out on hiking trails, mountain biking, or under the shade of mango trees." To plug into the island’s great outdoors, the family built an off-grid retreat on 2.5 acres that optimizes indoor/outdoor living. Bundit Kanisthakhon, a principal at @tadpole_studio, designed an airy, rectangular volume with a nearly wraparound deck and a double-height living/dining area at the home’s center that opens on two sides—a play on the traditional Hawaiian lanai. Though the modest cabin the family first imagined expanded from 600 to 925 square feet, the Davises retained their goal of living off-grid. There’s a propane refrigerator and cooktop, and two 100-watt solar panels that provide electricity. A well and a 1,500-gallon cistern keep the home supplied with water. When cloudy days mean no power, the family takes it in stride. "You’re back in the Laura Ingalls Wilder days of carrying your bucket out to the tank and filling it up so you can do the dishes," says James. "At night we’ll take our lanterns outside and make a campfire. You see the stars much more clearly, and you just have that camping sort of feel." See the full feature of Camp Davis from our July/August issue at the link in our bio, or when you pick up your own copy of the magazine.

Alix Petit (@alix.petit.kece) and Onur Keçe (@therefreshmentclub) had looked at numerous properties, but none measured up to a traditional stone house they first visited in the fall of 2018. Built in 1892 at the edge of a forest northwest of Paris, the house, with a three-story tower and an attached ivy-covered barn, was part of a compound that also included two additional one-room structures. "The garden was like a jungle—but that is what we loved about it," says Onur, adding that he and Alix, both of whom are creative directors at their own companies, were looking for something they could completely tear apart and redesign for their young family of four. The couple would let the exteriors of the home be, but reimagined the interiors as a clean-lined ode to concrete and immersive swaths of color. Onur visualized open, minimalist spaces, and Alix, who’s "a big hater of white walls,” says Onur, designed pink-tinted concrete countertops and bespoke patterned tiles in the kitchen, along with similarly patterned curtains in the barn—all referencing the vibrant fabrics she creates for her clothing brand, @heimstone. For the walls and ceilings, she chose an array of lime-based paints applied with a technique known as chaux ferrée, which produces a textured effect like that of Venetian painted plaster. "My eyes are always much more responsive to colors and patterns than to plain, white things," Alix explains. From our July/August issue, see how an overgrown 19th-century home now conceals a minimalist tableau rich with color.

The founders of @farouki.farouki, a New Orleans architecture and interior design firm, Caroline and Sabri Farouki are behind some of the city’s most visually striking spaces, from the glittery brasserie Justine in the French Quarter to The Odeon at South Market. In a city synonymous with old-world aesthetics, the modern, minimalist home they designed on an empty lot—space that’s hard to come by in a historic neighborhood—is easy to pick out. The front does not feature classic hurricane shutters but sleek, black-framed windows. The petite balcony was a concession to local regulations that the couple now agree gives the house a more copacetic, European appeal in the neighborhood. Inside, the home’s layout is flipped, with the bedrooms for the couple and their two sons downstairs and the living areas and kitchen above to maximize open space and natural light. From a roof deck, the family can take in the neighborhood’s history. "The view was a big surprise for us—and the best surprise," Sabri says. "We never got to see that aspect of the lot when we bought it. The house celebrates New Orleans out of every window." From our July/August issue, see the Farouki’s minimalist home when you pick up a copy of the magazine, or head to the link in our bio.

In Malinalco, Mexico, Casa Mague draws inspiration from the region’s Aztec heritage. “Piramide de Malinalco, one of only three carved pyramids in the world, is part of the town’s daily life,” explains Mauricio Ceballos Pressler, the director and founder of @mcxa.group. “The inhabitants feel proud of their Aztec roots.” To honor them, and in direct reference to the nearby pyramid, an exterior living area adjacent to the pool in the first slide features a curved and stepped wood wall. To more broadly echo a Mesoamerican worldview, Pressler designed each room of the 2,906-square-foot home to feel as if it’s woven into the landscape. “Trees have ritual meaning,” he explains. “The roots symbolize the connection to the underworld, the trunks symbolize the earthly human life, and the branches symbolize the connection with the Gods.” For more on how Casa Mague taps into its cultural roots, head to the link in bio.

After a multi-year search for the perfect midcentury gem to remodel, Los Angeles–based designers Whitney Brown and Carlos Naude stumbled across a neglected 1960s ranch-style home in Woodland Hills and immediately put in an offer. “The house was a diamond in the rough,” says Carlos. “It had great bones—it just needed to be brought back to life.”
Fortunately, the young couple, who are founders of the design firm @workingholidaystudio, were up to the challenge.
The couple sought to “create a place that felt very serene and calming,” says Whitney, explaining why they named their home the Zen Den. “We’ve always been inspired by the sleek minimalism of Scandinavian and Japanese designs,” she adds, noting they also integrated Mexican influences into the space as a way to celebrate Carlos’s heritage. Carlos says, “Overall, we wanted the house to be soothing and easy on the eye.”
A key ingredient the couple relied on for achieving maximum zen was natural light. “From the start, we knew that by installing new doors and windows, the entire aesthetic of the home would change—and that’s exactly what happened,” says Whitney. After researching various companies, the couple decided that @western_window_systems was the perfect fit. “We wanted windows and doors that looked streamlined and modern, but also met all standards of sustainability,” explains Carlos. Throughout the residence, the couple added skylights, picture windows, and sliding doors to draw in light while framing views of the surrounding canyons. “Outdoor living was a big reason we purchased this house,” says Whitney. “Installing the swing-out doors in the dining room was a game changer.”
“Now that the renovation is complete, we don’t want to leave home,” says Whitney. “Being a bit outside of the city, it feels like a vacation. To be able to lay in the grass in peace and quiet while having your child and dog play and run around—it’s truly a gift.” Tour the Japandi-inspired Zen Den at the link in bio.
